Tweet Text: 23) So, to be clear, I *do* think that the above claims might be true: Facebook wanted to distract people from its reputation and its lack of headroom for growth, and so it became Meta. But I think there's probably something else, too. Something that explains the next $10b.

Tweet Text: 22) Which makes no sense if this is all a diversion. It's one thing to blow $10b/year on smoke bombs. It's another thing to blow $10b/year on smoke bombs that don't produce very much smoke. Why throw good money after bad?

Tweet Text: 21) Except there's one last problem. Investors have now decided that spending $10b per year on The Metaverse is dumb, and Facebook (er, sorry, Meta)'s stock is tanking. The vague meta guidance is no longer working. And yet Zuck keeps spending. https://t.co/rkaAhS67OY

Tweet Text: 13) What's important is that we not bleed over from blacklists to whitelists. That sanctioning North Korea doesn't slowly slip into only allowing economic activity with a few trusted parties.
Original Author Description (Bio): CEO of @FTX_Official: https://t.co/O8fd1pXUIU. Not investment advice. https://t.co/cIqm5ibaMY and FTT not available in the United States or prohibited jurisdictions. https://t.co/pnF88iZt2b works in US!

Tweet Text: 12) And so what does that mean for, e.g., Tornado Cash being sanctioned? I think, basically: I understand why it happened, and that it's important to prevent illicit finance. And it was still a blacklist--if an extensive one--not enforcing a whitelist for transfers.
Original Author Description (Bio): CEO of @FTX_Official: https://t.co/O8fd1pXUIU. Not investment advice. https://t.co/cIqm5ibaMY and FTT not available in the United States or prohibited jurisdictions. https://t.co/pnF88iZt2b works in US!

Tweet Text: 11) You get most of the protection by blacklisting a few bad actors; and you get most of the freedom by otherwise allowing free commerce.
Original Author Description (Bio): CEO of @FTX_Official: https://t.co/O8fd1pXUIU. Not investment advice. https://t.co/cIqm5ibaMY and FTT not available in the United States or prohibited jurisdictions. https://t.co/pnF88iZt2b works in US!

Tweet Text: 10) I think this is a good compromise. Why? Because: a) it means that anyone who is facilitating financial crimes can be blacklisted by e.g. OFAC and cut off b) but for everyone else, transfers just work: they're seamless and permissionless.
Original Author Description (Bio): CEO of @FTX_Official: https://t.co/O8fd1pXUIU. Not investment advice. https://t.co/cIqm5ibaMY and FTT not available in the United States or prohibited jurisdictions. https://t.co/pnF88iZt2b works in US!

Tweet Text: 9) In other words, crypto uses a blacklist system: you can't send funds to/from a person or entity that is specifically blacklisted, but otherwise you are free to do as you wish (at least for peer to peer transfers).
Original Author Description (Bio): CEO of @FTX_Official: https://t.co/O8fd1pXUIU. Not investment advice. https://t.co/cIqm5ibaMY and FTT not available in the United States or prohibited jurisdictions. https://t.co/pnF88iZt2b works in US!

Tweet Text: 8) So what does crypto do? Well, right now, if Alice wants to send $100 to Bob: a) if Alice or Bob are sanctioned--e.g. on an OFAC list--then it is generally illegal. b) otherwise, it is generally legal also, crypto transfers are not reversible.
Original Author Description (Bio): CEO of @FTX_Official: https://t.co/O8fd1pXUIU. Not investment advice. https://t.co/cIqm5ibaMY and FTT not available in the United States or prohibited jurisdictions. https://t.co/pnF88iZt2b works in US!

Tweet Text: 7) Safety vs Freedom, I guess. Whitelists--like how ACH works today--provide lots of safety. But they make transfers, innovation, and commerce very difficult. Free systems--like cash--are clean and simple and, well free. But they could be used to launder money.
Original Author Description (Bio): CEO of @FTX_Official: https://t.co/O8fd1pXUIU. Not investment advice. https://t.co/cIqm5ibaMY and FTT not available in the United States or prohibited jurisdictions. https://t.co/pnF88iZt2b works in US!

Tweet Text: 6) There are tradeoffs here. In favor of restricting transfers: a) you can cut off terrorists b) you can protect customers who accidentally sent money Against: c) state overreach for political reasons (economic censorship) d) commerce is much clunkier and doesn't 'just work'
Original Author Description (Bio): CEO of @FTX_Official: https://t.co/O8fd1pXUIU. Not investment advice. https://t.co/cIqm5ibaMY and FTT not available in the United States or prohibited jurisdictions. https://t.co/pnF88iZt2b works in US!

Tweet Text: 5) So ACH uses a whitelist system: you can only send someone money if a set of institutions have explicitly said so. Cash just always works, as do bars of gold.
Original Author Description (Bio): CEO of @FTX_Official: https://t.co/O8fd1pXUIU. Not investment advice. https://t.co/cIqm5ibaMY and FTT not available in the United States or prohibited jurisdictions. https://t.co/pnF88iZt2b works in US!

Tweet Text: 4) Right now: a) cash is essentially fully free. You can hand a dollar bill to anyone. It's never reversible. b) ACH transfers only work from one person who has been whitelisted for an account at a bank that's whitelisted by the fed, to another. And they can be reversed!

Tweet Text: 19) The flipside of overfit, irrelevant data: fermi estimates. Trying to estimate quantitative factors without knowing all the relevant data is hard, but you can often get reasonable bounds on it. And those bounds can be extremely useful.
Original Author Description (Bio): CEO of @FTX_Official: https://t.co/O8fd1pXUIU. Not investment advice. https://t.co/cIqm5ibaMY and FTT not available in the United States or prohibited jurisdictions. https://t.co/pnF88iZt2b works in US!

Tweet Text: 18) But aimlessly generating data just distracts. It's also very similar to a trap that some interview candidates fall into, particularly those with strong math backgrounds: Given a hard, messy question, they'll try to solve it exactly. And if they can't, they get flummoxed.
Original Author Description (Bio): CEO of @FTX_Official: https://t.co/O8fd1pXUIU. Not investment advice. https://t.co/cIqm5ibaMY and FTT not available in the United States or prohibited jurisdictions. https://t.co/pnF88iZt2b works in US!

Tweet Text: 17) If you've thought hard about a decision you have to make and think you really understand the various factors, and know which factor you're uncertain about, then it can be *extremely* helpful to get some data!
Original Author Description (Bio): CEO of @FTX_Official: https://t.co/O8fd1pXUIU. Not investment advice. https://t.co/cIqm5ibaMY and FTT not available in the United States or prohibited jurisdictions. https://t.co/pnF88iZt2b works in US!

Tweet Text: 16) And this is a failure mode that a _lot_ of people fall into. The vast majority of statistics that I see quoted are useless. The times when stats are more likely to be useful are when they are answering a very specific, intentional question.
Original Author Description (Bio): CEO of @FTX_Official: https://t.co/O8fd1pXUIU. Not investment advice. https://t.co/cIqm5ibaMY and FTT not available in the United States or prohibited jurisdictions. https://t.co/pnF88iZt2b works in US!

Tweet Text: 15) And as our world becomes richer and richer in data--and as it becomes more commonplace to use it and cite it--it's getting misused more and more. (see also https://t.co/vwUgxFZzsm)
Original Author Description (Bio): CEO of @FTX_Official: https://t.co/O8fd1pXUIU. Not investment advice. https://t.co/cIqm5ibaMY and FTT not available in the United States or prohibited jurisdictions. https://t.co/pnF88iZt2b works in US!

Tweet Text: 14) But if you do a mediocre job of using data, it just adds noise which distracts you from your baseline reasonable judgement. There is a fairly high bar that statistical analysis has to overcome to be net useful!
Original Author Description (Bio): CEO of @FTX_Official: https://t.co/O8fd1pXUIU. Not investment advice. https://t.co/cIqm5ibaMY and FTT not available in the United States or prohibited jurisdictions. https://t.co/pnF88iZt2b works in US!

Tweet Text: 13) And in this case, a simple gut check might have made Zed realize that _obviously_ superbowl ads have large impact, and a lot of that is the chatter. So there are lots of ways to use data poorly. That doesn't make it useless--there are also lots of ways to use it well!
Original Author Description (Bio): CEO of @FTX_Official: https://t.co/O8fd1pXUIU. Not investment advice. https://t.co/cIqm5ibaMY and FTT not available in the United States or prohibited jurisdictions. https://t.co/pnF88iZt2b works in US!

Tweet Text: 12) And how about Zed? Well, what, in the end, is an impression? One of the important properties about superbowl ads: they're talked about again and again and again, in lots of places that are hard to track. The direct views significantly underestimate it's impact.
Original Author Description (Bio): CEO of @FTX_Official: https://t.co/O8fd1pXUIU. Not investment advice. https://t.co/cIqm5ibaMY and FTT not available in the United States or prohibited jurisdictions. https://t.co/pnF88iZt2b works in US!

Tweet Text: 11) Yes, there is a positive correlation between having 10k employees and being successful: You can only hire 10k employees if you've done well. So there's a correlation, but the direction of causation is probably wrong.
Original Author Description (Bio): CEO of @FTX_Official: https://t.co/O8fd1pXUIU. Not investment advice. https://t.co/cIqm5ibaMY and FTT not available in the United States or prohibited jurisdictions. https://t.co/pnF88iZt2b works in US!

Tweet Text: 10) Bob probably would have been better just saying "let's build the business that seems the best" and ignoring valuation. In Alice's case, her data is probably being misinterpreted.
Original Author Description (Bio): CEO of @FTX_Official: https://t.co/O8fd1pXUIU. Not investment advice. https://t.co/cIqm5ibaMY and FTT not available in the United States or prohibited jurisdictions. https://t.co/pnF88iZt2b works in US!

Tweet Text: 9) In Bob's case, his data is technically correct! But there are two core issues: a) his revenue might not be the same in both cases; maybe the mobile app makes more than 4x as much revenue as the B2B product. b) also: valuation isn't all that matters! I'd prefer earnings.
Original Author Description (Bio): CEO of @FTX_Official: https://t.co/O8fd1pXUIU. Not investment advice. https://t.co/cIqm5ibaMY and FTT not available in the United States or prohibited jurisdictions. https://t.co/pnF88iZt2b works in US!

Tweet Text: 8) The key insight: you're not choosing between looking at statistics or acing randomly. You have a prior coming in: based on your intuition and critical thinking. The question is whether data is more or less useful than your priors, and whether you combine them well.
Original Author Description (Bio): CEO of @FTX_Official: https://t.co/O8fd1pXUIU. Not investment advice. https://t.co/cIqm5ibaMY and FTT not available in the United States or prohibited jurisdictions. https://t.co/pnF88iZt2b works in US!

Tweet Text: 7) Each of these scenarios are a bit different, and I don't necessarily know what the right answer is in all of them. But in each case, the statistics were (a) reasonable, (b) correct, and (c) net harmful to their decision making process.
Original Author Description (Bio): CEO of @FTX_Official: https://t.co/O8fd1pXUIU. Not investment advice. https://t.co/cIqm5ibaMY and FTT not available in the United States or prohibited jurisdictions. https://t.co/pnF88iZt2b works in US!

Tweet Text: 6) c) Zed is trying to decide whether to do a superbowl commercial, or a Facebook ad. They look at impressions per dollar, and decide the latter is cheaper; so they forgo the game.
Original Author Description (Bio): CEO of @FTX_Official: https://t.co/O8fd1pXUIU. Not investment advice. https://t.co/cIqm5ibaMY and FTT not available in the United States or prohibited jurisdictions. https://t.co/pnF88iZt2b works in US!

Tweet Text: 5) b) Alice is at a VC firm. She does a study of the correlation between employee count and market cap for their portfolio companies. Controlling for lots of other factors, it's +75%. In the next round, she mostly funds companies rapidly expanding their headcount.
Original Author Description (Bio): CEO of @FTX_Official: https://t.co/O8fd1pXUIU. Not investment advice. https://t.co/cIqm5ibaMY and FTT not available in the United States or prohibited jurisdictions. https://t.co/pnF88iZt2b works in US!

Tweet Text: 4) Some examples: a) Bob is running a consumer fintech company. He studies the multiples of exchange fees and B2B subscription fees; he finds that they're 20x and 80x, respectively. So he decides against building a mobile interface, and focuses on being a B2B liquidity source.
Original Author Description (Bio): CEO of @FTX_Official: https://t.co/O8fd1pXUIU. Not investment advice. https://t.co/cIqm5ibaMY and FTT not available in the United States or prohibited jurisdictions. https://t.co/pnF88iZt2b works in US!

Tweet Text: 3) But the truth is that I think most people misuse, and overuse, statistics. So much so, that many people would be better off ignoring data than what they're currently doing. I think it took me a while to come to terms with this.

Tweet Text: 15) These are some of the issues at the heart of our @CFTC application: https://t.co/1bvp3U4sVD
Original Author Description (Bio): CEO of @FTX_Official: https://t.co/O8fd1pXUIU. Not investment advice. https://t.co/cIqm5ibaMY and FTT not available in the United States or prohibited jurisdictions. https://t.co/pnF88iZt2b works in US!

Tweet Text: 14) This exacerbated the original problem--instead of eating 1 day's risk, they were eating 3 days'. Another difference with crypto markets, which operate 24/7--allowing 24/7 margin calculations and de-leveraging.
Original Author Description (Bio): CEO of @FTX_Official: https://t.co/O8fd1pXUIU. Not investment advice. https://t.co/cIqm5ibaMY and FTT not available in the United States or prohibited jurisdictions. https://t.co/pnF88iZt2b works in US!

Tweet Text: 13) Anyway, that's one of the core innovations of digital asset exchanges--real-time margining. The other problem that LME Nickel ran into was the weekend. The exchange wasn't open for a few days, and so the _fastest_ they could margin call was 72 hours.
Original Author Description (Bio): CEO of @FTX_Official: https://t.co/O8fd1pXUIU. Not investment advice. https://t.co/cIqm5ibaMY and FTT not available in the United States or prohibited jurisdictions. https://t.co/pnF88iZt2b works in US!

Tweet Text: 12) This is how liquidations work on FTX--we begin de-leveraging a position as soon as it's running too low on collateral, independent of how long it's been. We *have* to--that's the only way we can stop things like this! Sometimes 1 day is too long. https://t.co/B1WBovpJOh
Original Author Description (Bio): CEO of @FTX_Official: https://t.co/O8fd1pXUIU. Not investment advice. https://t.co/cIqm5ibaMY and FTT not available in the United States or prohibited jurisdictions. https://t.co/pnF88iZt2b works in US!

Tweet Text: 11) So in this hypothetical, you have to begin liquidating X's position when the contract hits $1.50. completely independently of _when_ that happens. If a week later the contract is at $1.35, it's fine. But if a minute later it's at $1.50, it's time to start closing down X.
Original Author Description (Bio): CEO of @FTX_Official: https://t.co/O8fd1pXUIU. Not investment advice. https://t.co/cIqm5ibaMY and FTT not available in the United States or prohibited jurisdictions. https://t.co/pnF88iZt2b works in US!

Tweet Text: 10) Say that closing down X's position--buying back 3b contracts--would have 10% impact. The means that, if X isn't going to top up, you have to start reducing their position before the contract hits around $1.50--adding 10% impact to that would impact markets to around $1.66.
Original Author Description (Bio): CEO of @FTX_Official: https://t.co/O8fd1pXUIU. Not investment advice. https://t.co/cIqm5ibaMY and FTT not available in the United States or prohibited jurisdictions. https://t.co/pnF88iZt2b works in US!

Tweet Text: 9) Which means--the goal is for X to de-leverage before the contract reaches $1.66. Time is arbitrary! The contract could move 1% in 3 days, or it could move 150%. What matters is the price. You have to close down before contracts hit $1.66.
Original Author Description (Bio): CEO of @FTX_Official: https://t.co/O8fd1pXUIU. Not investment advice. https://t.co/cIqm5ibaMY and FTT not available in the United States or prohibited jurisdictions. https://t.co/pnF88iZt2b works in US!

Tweet Text: 8) The goal of the margin call: before X runs out of collateral, either (a) X tops up their collateral (b) X reduces their position Once the contract reaches a price of $1.66, X will fully run out of collateral; any move beyond that and X goes _negative_ account value.
Original Author Description (Bio): CEO of @FTX_Official: https://t.co/O8fd1pXUIU. Not investment advice. https://t.co/cIqm5ibaMY and FTT not available in the United States or prohibited jurisdictions. https://t.co/pnF88iZt2b works in US!

Tweet Text: 7) There are really two problems here. First, the exchange margin calls based on _time_, not _price_. What does that mean? Well, when X reaches 6x leverage on a $4b position, it's time to issue a margin call.
Original Author Description (Bio): CEO of @FTX_Official: https://t.co/O8fd1pXUIU. Not investment advice. https://t.co/cIqm5ibaMY and FTT not available in the United States or prohibited jurisdictions. https://t.co/pnF88iZt2b works in US!

Tweet Text: 6) By the time the next business day ends, there have been 3 days for volatility. A 25% move bankrupts the trader. A 50% move means that someone's out $1b of insurance. That could happen in 3 days! And, in fact, it did, in Nickel. (Note the weekend gap!) https://t.co/0JcOymVSAR
Original Author Description (Bio): CEO of @FTX_Official: https://t.co/O8fd1pXUIU. Not investment advice. https://t.co/cIqm5ibaMY and FTT not available in the United States or prohibited jurisdictions. https://t.co/pnF88iZt2b works in US!

Tweet Text: 5) The traditional margin model says: reach out to X and warn then to top up, _or else_. But X has at least a business day to top up. If it's a Friday evening, then they have at least 72 hours. Except there's a war going on in Ukraine, and commodity prices are skyrocketing.
Original Author Description (Bio): CEO of @FTX_Official: https://t.co/O8fd1pXUIU. Not investment advice. https://t.co/cIqm5ibaMY and FTT not available in the United States or prohibited jurisdictions. https://t.co/pnF88iZt2b works in US!

Tweet Text: 4) X now has a huge position on, and is fairly leveraged--$4b notional, 4x leverage. Another 25% move and the trader is underwater; each 25% move beyond that costs _someone_ -- the exchange, or insurance, or whatever is backstopping it -- about $1b!
Original Author Description (Bio): CEO of @FTX_Official: https://t.co/O8fd1pXUIU. Not investment advice. https://t.co/cIqm5ibaMY and FTT not available in the United States or prohibited jurisdictions. https://t.co/pnF88iZt2b works in US!

Tweet Text: 3) Let's say that some entity (X) has $2b of collateral and puts on a $3b short in a contract trading at $1 (so 3b contracts). Markets start to go up in price--eventually they're at $1.33. Now the trader has: position size: 3b contracts = $4b collateral: $1b

Tweet Text: 10) "But this was Bill's job" is not a relevant excuse for someone with a fancy title. Our job is to make sure the right things get done, whatever it takes. And ultimately, _my_ job is to make sure the right things happen.
Original Author Description (Bio): CEO of @FTX_Official: https://t.co/O8fd1pXUIU. Not investment advice. https://t.co/cIqm5ibaMY and FTT not available in the United States or prohibited jurisdictions. https://t.co/pnF88iZt2b works in US!

Tweet Text: 9) If you have a title, that doesn't mean you get credit if your team does something cool--they do. Having a title means you are held accountable if something important _doesn't_ get done, no matter who was "supposed" to do it.
Original Author Description (Bio): CEO of @FTX_Official: https://t.co/O8fd1pXUIU. Not investment advice. https://t.co/cIqm5ibaMY and FTT not available in the United States or prohibited jurisdictions. https://t.co/pnF88iZt2b works in US!

Tweet Text: 8) And this leads into our philosophy on titles. A title isn't an invitation to do important things, because everyone can do important things, and is expected to. A title is a burden: the responsibility to _make sure_ important things happen.
Original Author Description (Bio): CEO of @FTX_Official: https://t.co/O8fd1pXUIU. Not investment advice. https://t.co/cIqm5ibaMY and FTT not available in the United States or prohibited jurisdictions. https://t.co/pnF88iZt2b works in US!

Tweet Text: 7) And if there's a problem to fix or opportunity to grow, and you have an idea for it, the default behavior isn't to email a report asking them to do it. The default behavior is to do it: to take responsibility. Even our "managers" are > 50% individual contributors.
Original Author Description (Bio): CEO of @FTX_Official: https://t.co/O8fd1pXUIU. Not investment advice. https://t.co/cIqm5ibaMY and FTT not available in the United States or prohibited jurisdictions. https://t.co/pnF88iZt2b works in US!

Tweet Text: 6) And as employees look around, they see people all over doing exactly that. And by having way more to do than we have capacity to do it, we gain another benefit: there isn't really competition internally to get the "important" roles. We have important roles growing on trees.
Original Author Description (Bio): CEO of @FTX_Official: https://t.co/O8fd1pXUIU. Not investment advice. https://t.co/cIqm5ibaMY and FTT not available in the United States or prohibited jurisdictions. https://t.co/pnF88iZt2b works in US!

Tweet Text: 5) One of the subtle advantages to having a smaller team is the impact it has on responsibility and culture. We try to foster a sense of responsibility in every employee--that there are huge numbers of important things to do, and we should all feel empowered to help do them.

Tweet Text: The biggest problem with taxing unrealized gains: Let's say you start a company, and it starts doing well. The market value of the equity you have goes up. You owe tax on it.... way more than your cash. So you're *forced* to sell any time it goes up to get $ to pay tax.

Tweet Text: 8) So we run into Weird Thing #1: often companies will disguise scaling expenses as fixed expenses, and then VCs will invest in them at way too high of a valuation, thinking they have a business model that scales well!

Tweet Text: 7) So, in theory, you should calculate something like "net revenue" -- raw revenue minus expenses that scale with revenue. But the thing is, it's often hard to tell which expenses are which -- _especially_ if you're an investor and not the company itself!
